\begin_layout Section
Discussion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Throughout this study, the various fluids have been assumed to be immiscible.
 Whilst this is a common assumption in situations where mixing is low or
 practically non-existent, there are many problems which may require it.
 It should be fairly straightforward to implement a mixture model such as
 that proposed by Romenski et al.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Romenski2007,Romenski2010"

\end_inset

, which uses the same thermal conduction system as the GPR model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Riemann Ghost Fluid Method presented in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "sec:An HPR Riemann Ghost Fluid Method"

\end_inset

 has been demonstrated to be a viable way of accurately simulating the interface
s between different materials described by the GPR model.
 Unlike in many existing implementations, heat conduction across the interface
 was simulated accurately.
 This greatly simplifies the conceptual framework required for multiphase
 interactions, as described in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "subsec:Multiphase-Systems"

\end_inset

.
 Implementation should be easier and quicker, and future work can be more
 focused on a single model, rather than several fundamentally different
 frameworks.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Limitations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The truncation of the Taylor series expansions 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:q* Taylor Series"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:sigma* Taylor Series"

\end_inset

 used to find the star states of the heat flux and the viscous stress tensor
 implicitly assumes that there are only small differences between the side
 states and the star states of the variables upon which 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}^{*},\boldsymbol{\sigma_{1}^{*}}$
\end_inset

 depend (
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{1}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{A_{1}}$
\end_inset

).
 If this is the case, higher order terms of the expansion can be neglected.
 If it is not, however, the method may fail.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The linearised nature of the GPR-RGFM solver also implicitly assumes that
 all waves of interest present in the Riemann Problem are shocks.
 Thus, strong rarefactions may cause the method to fail.
 An example of this is the failure of the GPR-RGFM on the water-gas shock
 tube test (taken from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Chinnayya2004"

\end_inset

).
 The domain 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

 is initially occupied on 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,0.7\right]$
\end_inset

 by water (with material parameters given in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "sec:Water-Water Interface"

\end_inset

) and on 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(0.7,1\right]$
\end_inset

 by air (with material parameters given in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
